THE GAP: MANAGING A DIGITAL MEDIEVAL INITIATIVE ACROSS DISCIPLINES AND INSTITUTIONS / rKoivisto, Joseph / Kopár, Lilla / Wicker, Nancy L. -- tINDEX  aThis book looks at the intersection between medieval studies and digital humanities, confronting how medievalists negotiate the "virtual divide" between the cultural artefacts that they study and the digital means by which they address those artefacts. The essays come from medievalists who have created digital resources or applied digital tools and methodologies in their scholarship. Text encoding and analysis, data modeling and provenance, and 3D design are all discussed as they apply to western European medieval literature, history, art history, and architecture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Jun 2019) 4aDigital Humanities. 4acollaborative research. 4amedieval studies. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Library & Information Science / Digital & Online Resources.2bisacsh1 aDavis, Matthew Evan, eeditor.1 aMahoney-Steel, Tamsyn, eeditor.1 aTurnator, Ece, eeditor.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781641891936zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781641891936.jpg  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG